Que 1. What is abstraction in Java and how is it achieved?
Ans: 	Abstraction is focus on hiding implementation details and showing only essential details to user.
		Mainly focus on what to do not how to do.
		
		How is it achieved:
		A. Abstract Class:
			A class cannot initiated and it contain abstract method (without body) and concrete method (With body).
			Using abstract class only partially abstraction is possible.
			Declare using as 'abstract' name.
			
			abstract class Fruit{ //abstract method
				abstract void color();
				
				void taste(); //concrete method 
				system.out.println("Delicious...")
			}
			
			class Mango extends Fruit{
				@overide
				 void color(){
				 	System.out.println("COlor is yellow...")
				 }
			}
			
		B. Interface:
			A interface is reference type in java. It only contain abstract method and default and static methods (in java 8+).
			Using interface we can achieved 100% abstraction.
			
			inteface bike{
				void ride();
			}
			
			class Active implements bike{
				@override
				 public void ride(){
				 		System.out.println("Riding Activa..");
				 }
			}
			
******************************************************************************************************************************
					
Que 2. Can we create an object of an abstract class? Why or why not?
Ans:	No, we cannot create an object of an abstract class.
		abstract class contains may contains the abstract methods,
		abstract methods don not have body, for an object must be need a body to be useful.
			 
		class Animal{
			abstract void sound();
		}
		
		public class test{
			public static void main(String[] args){
				Animal a = new Animal(); //compile error
			}
		}

******************************************************************************************************************************

Que 3. How does method overriding work with abstract classes?
Ans: 	Using method overriding only we have access the abstract class abstract method.
		Abstract method declare only without body.
		A subclass must be override the all abstract methods.
		
		class Animal{
			abstract void sound(); //abstract method
		}
		class Dog extends Animal{
		 @override
		 public void sound (){
		 system.out.println("Dog barks")
		 }
		}
		public class test{
			public static void main(String[] args){
				Animal a = new Dog); 
				a.sound();			
				}
		}
		
******************************************************************************************************************************

Que 4. What’s the difference between abstract class and interface?
Ans: Abstract Class:
		Abstract declare using 'abstract' word.
		Abstract class may contains the abstract method and concrete method.
		class inherit from only one abstract class.
		For methods and variable access modifier can be public, private and protected.
		Using abstract class only partially abstraction is possible.
		
		
		Example:
			abstract class Fruit{ //abstract method
				abstract void color();
				
				void taste(); //concrete method 
				system.out.println("Delicious...")
			}
		
		
		
	Interface: 
		Interface declare using 'interface' word.
		Interface by default include abstract method, In java 8+ version included the default and static methods as well.
		Class implement from multiple interface. 
		For methods and variable access modifier implicitly only public.
		Using interface we can achieved 100% abstraction.
		
			inteface bike{
				void ride();
			}
			
			class Active implements bike{
				@override
				 public void ride(){
				 		System.out.println("Riding Activa..");
				 }
			}
		

******************************************************************************************************************************

Que 5. Explain the concept of call by value in Java with an example.
Ans: Call by value only a copy of variable value is passed to methods.
	 Change made inside the method do not affect the original variable.
	 
	 class CallByValueDemo{
	 	void change(int x){
	 		x = 50;
	 	}
	 	
	 public static void main(String[] args){
	 		int a = 10;
	 		change(a);
	 		system.out.println("a = " + a)
	 	}
	 }

******************************************************************************************************************************
