6. Does Java support call by reference? Justify your answer.
Ans: No, java does not support the call by reference. Java strictly call by value.
	 But objects are passed by reference value. So modifications inside method affect the object.
	 Java is always pass-by-value, but for objects, the value of reference (address) is passed.
	 
	 class Student {
	    int marks;
		}

	class Test {
	    void change(Student s) {
	        s.marks = 90;   // modifies object field
	    }
	
	    public static void main(String[] args) {
	        Student st = new Student();
	        st.marks = 50;
	
	        change(st);
	        System.out.println(st.marks);
	    }
	}

	
	
******************************************************************************************************************************

Que 7. How are primitive data types passed to methods in Java?
Ans: Primitive data types in java are passed by value.
	 A copy of primitive value is passed to the method.

	class Test{
		void change(int x){
		 x = 100;
		}
	}
	
	public static void main(String[] args){
		int num = 10;
		change(num);
	}

