Que 8. What happens when we pass an object to a method in Java?
Ans:	Java passes the a copy of the object reference(address), not object it self.
		
		class Student{
			int marks;
		}
		 class test{
		 	void change(Student s){
		 		s.marks = 90;
		 	}
		 	
		 	public statis void main(String[] args){
		 		Student st = new Studen();
		 		st.marks = 50;
		 		
		 		change(st);
		 		system.out.println(st.marks)
		 	}
		 }
		 
******************************************************************************************************************************

Que 9. Why do changes to an object’s field reflect outside the method?
Ans: Java passes a copy of the object reference by value and both the caller and method point to the same object in memory.
	 Java passes the a copy of the object reference(address), not object it self.
	 
		class Student {
		    int marks;
		}
		
		class Test {
		    void change(Student s) {
		        s.marks = 90;   // modifies object field
		    }
		
		    public static void main(String[] args) {
		        Student st = new Student();
		        st.marks = 50;
		
		        change(st);
		        System.out.println(st.marks);
		    }
		}
	 
******************************************************************************************************************************
Que 10. Can an abstract class have a constructor or static block?
Ans: Yes, abstract class have a constructor or static block.

	  Constructor:
	  
	  abstract class Animal{
	  	Animal(){ 		//class Constructor
	  		system.out.println("Animal constructor.")
	  	}
	  	abstract void sound();
	  }
	  class Dog extends Animal{
	  	@override
	  	void sound(){
	  		system.out.println("Dog barks.")
	  	}
	  }
	public class AbstractConstructors{
		public static void main(String[] args){
			Animal an = new Dog()
			an.sound();
		}
	}
	
	--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
	
	static block:
	
	abstract class Animal{
		abstract void sound();
		
		static{
			system.out.println("Animal static block..")
		}
	}
	
	class Dog extends Animal {
	@override
	void sound(){
		system.out.println("Dog sound..")
	}
	}
	
	public class AbstractStatic{
		public static void main(String[] args){
			Animal a = new Dog();
			a.sound();
		}
	}
	
	











